---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="How this site makes money"
  description="The full policy: affiliate links in articles only, always disclosed, chosen before money is considered. No display ads, ever. The tool is free and unconnected to any of it."
>
  <div class="wrap prose">
    <section class="section">
      <h1>How this site makes money</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Mostly, it does not. Here is the whole picture, so you never have to
        wonder what a recommendation is worth.
      </p>

      <h2>The tool is free and unconnected to any of it</h2>
      <p>
        Executor File is free, open source and MIT licensed. There is no paid
        tier, no upsell inside it, and nothing on the{' '}
        <a href="/get-started">Get started</a> or{' '}
        <a href="/recover">For executors</a> pages is monetised in any way.
        Those pages carry no affiliate links and never will.
      </p>

      <h2>Some article links pay a commission</h2>
      <p>
        Articles under <a href="/learn">Learn</a> sometimes recommend products:
        password managers, will-writing services, fireproof safes, books. Some
        of those links pay this site a commission when you buy. Three rules
        govern them:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Recommendations are chosen before money is considered.</strong> We recommend what we would tell a friend to use, then check whether an affiliate programme happens to exist, in that order.</li>
        <li><strong>Every page with affiliate links says so at the top</strong>, before the links, not in a footer.</li>
        <li><strong>Free options are recommended alongside paying ones.</strong> Several things we recommend pay nothing: free will-writing routes, free password-manager tiers, a do-it-yourself document safe. Their presence is the point; a recommendation list with no free options on it is an advert.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>A tip jar exists</h2>
      <p>
        There is a{' '}
        <a href="https://buymeacoffee.com/jamiewatters">Buy me a coffee</a>{' '}
        link in the footer. It is a tip, nothing more: it buys no features, no
        priority, no influence, and the tool stays free and complete whether
        anyone ever uses it or not. It does not appear on the recovery pages,
        which carry nothing commercial at all.
      </p>

      <h2>No display ads, ever</h2>
      <p>
        This site will never run display advertising. Programmatic ads around
        bereavement have a grim record, and a site whose core argument is that
        nothing here can exploit or outlive you cannot rent its pages to systems
        built to do both. This is policy, not a temporary state.
      </p>

      <h2>What that adds up to</h2>
      <p>
        At current traffic, coffee money. The structure exists so that the
        incentives are visible and right from the start, not because it funds
        anything. If that ever changes, this page changes with it.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
